explanation:
OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET - The macro (or inline accessor) computes 'impl' from the token and may perform validation, error handling, or side effects (e.g. return/abort). If it itself causes an early return or abort the remainder of the function could be unreachable.
OS_impl_dir_table - The global table passed to the macro; its layout or contents determine whether a valid 'impl' can be obtained and whether subsequent code can execute.
OS_impl_dir_internal_record_t - The type of 'impl' and, crucially, the 'dp' member (directory stream pointer). Knowledge of this type and whether 'dp' can be NULL or invalid is required to reason about whether readdir() can ever return non-NULL.
OS_object_token_t - The token value and its semantics (range/validation) are used by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; token semantics may make code paths unreachable if invalid tokens are rejected earlier.
OS_ObjectIndexFromToken - The static call graph shows this function is involved with object-table indexing; if the macro expands to call it, its behavior (returns, error handling, assertions) can make downstream code unreachable.
struct dirent - The definition (including d_name semantics and lifetime) is needed to reason about readdir() results and whether de->d_name can be used safely after readdir, which affects reachability of the strncpy branch.
readdir - Its specification/implementation: whether it can return NULL for given 'dp' or whether it can block/longjmp/abort. If readdir always returned NULL (or never returns) for the relevant dp, the non-NULL branch (and subsequent strncpy/OS_SUCCESS return) would be unreachable.
os_dirent_t - Definition of the output dirent (FileName member and its size). Knowing FileName size is necessary to assess the strncpy usage and whether that code is meaningful/reachable.
strncpy - The behavior of strncpy (or any replacement implementation) matters if it has side effects that could alter control flow; also used to reason whether the code after the de==NULL check is substantive.
OS_ERROR / OS_SUCCESS - The return macros/values used in the two return statements; needed to determine whether either return is optimized/rewritten by project-specific definitions (e.g. macros that longjmp/abort) which would affect reachability.
